#ideal butter worth gaussian 

import cv2
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# ---------- Distance Matrix ----------
def distance_matrix(M, N):
    u = np.arange(M) - M/2
    v = np.arange(N) - N/2
    V, U = np.meshgrid(v, u)
    return np.sqrt(U**2 + V**2)

# ---------- Low-pass Filters ----------
def ideal_lpf(D, D0):
    return (D <= D0).astype(float)

def butter_lpf(D, D0, n=2):
    return 1 / (1 + (D / D0)**(2*n))

def gaussian_lpf(D, D0):
    return np.exp(-(D**2) / (2*(D0**2)))

# ---------- MAIN ----------
# Load uploaded image
img = cv2.imread(r"C:\Users\Admin\OneDrive\Pictures\WhatsApp Image 2024-11-17 at 12.02.41_99fa69bd.jpg", 0)

# FFT
F = np.fft.fftshift(np.fft.fft2(img))
M, N = img.shape
D = distance_matrix(M, N)

# Use smaller cutoff for clear results
D0 = 60  

# Apply filters
ideal = np.abs(np.fft.ifft2(np.fft.ifftshift(F * ideal_lpf(D, D0))))
butter = np.abs(np.fft.ifft2(np.fft.ifftshift(F * butter_lpf(D, D0))))
gauss = np.abs(np.fft.ifft2(np.fft.ifftshift(F * gaussian_lpf(D, D0))))

# Combine output
final = np.hstack((ideal, butter, gauss))

# Show inside Jupyter
plt.figure(figsize=(12,4))
plt.imshow(final, cmap='gray')
plt.title("Ideal LPF | Butterworth LPF | Gaussian LPF")
plt.axis('off')
plt.show()

import cv2
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def distance_matrix(M, N):
    u = np.arange(M) - M/2
    v = np.arange(N) - N/2
    V, U = np.meshgrid(v, u)
    return np.sqrt(U**2 + V**2)

def ideal_hpf(D, D0):
    return (D > D0).astype(float)

def butterworth_hpf(D, D0, n=2):
    return 1 / (1 + (D0/(D+1e-6))**(2*n))

def gaussian_hpf(D, D0):
    return 1 - np.exp(-(D**2)/(2*(D0**2)))

#  Clean inverse FFT function
def apply_hpf(F, H):
    return np.abs(np.fft.ifft2(np.fft.ifftshift(F * H)))

# Load your image
img = cv2.imread(r"C:\Users\Admin\OneDrive\Pictures\Your paragraph text.png", 0)

# FFT
F = np.fft.fftshift(np.fft.fft2(img))
M, N = img.shape
D = distance_matrix(M, N)

D0 = 20

#  Super clean calls
ideal = apply_hpf(F, ideal_hpf(D, D0))
butter = apply_hpf(F, butterworth_hpf(D, D0))
gauss  = apply_hpf(F, gaussian_hpf(D, D0))

# Show
plt.figure(figsize=(15,4))
plt.subplot(1,3,1); plt.imshow(ideal, cmap='gray'); plt.title("Ideal HPF"); plt.axis('off')
plt.subplot(1,3,2); plt.imshow(butter, cmap='gray'); plt.title("Butterworth HPF"); plt.axis('off')
plt.subplot(1,3,3); plt.imshow(gauss, cmap='gray'); plt.title("Gaussian HPF"); plt.axis('off')
plt.show()

import cv2
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Load and convert to binary
img = cv2.imread(r"C:\Users\Admin\OneDrive\Pictures\Your paragraph text.png", 0)
_, binary = cv2.threshold(img, 127, 255, cv2.THRESH_BINARY)

# 33 structuring element
kernel = np.array([
    [1,1,1],
    [1,1,1],
    [1,1,1]
], dtype=np.uint8)

M, N = binary.shape
kM, kN = kernel.shape
pad = kM // 2

# ====================================================================
# ---------------------   EROSION (Manual)   --------------------------
# ====================================================================
def erosion(binary, kernel):
    padded = np.pad(binary, pad, mode='constant')
    eroded = np.zeros_like(binary)

    for i in range(M):
        for j in range(N):
            region = padded[i:i+kM, j:j+kN]
            fits = np.all(region[kernel == 1] == 255)
            eroded[i, j] = 255 if fits else 0

    return eroded


# ====================================================================
# ---------------------   DILATION (Manual)   -------------------------
# ====================================================================
def dilation(binary, kernel):
    padded = np.pad(binary, pad, mode='constant')
    dilated = np.zeros_like(binary)

    for i in range(M):
        for j in range(N):
            region = padded[i:i+kM, j:j+kN]
            hit = np.any(region[kernel == 1] == 255)
            dilated[i, j] = 255 if hit else 0

    return dilated


# ====================================================================
# ---------------------   OPENING = E  D   ---------------------------
# ====================================================================
opening_result = dilation(erosion(binary, kernel), kernel)

# ====================================================================
# ---------------------   CLOSING = D  E   ---------------------------
# ====================================================================
closing_result = erosion(dilation(binary, kernel), kernel)

# ====================================================================
# ---------------------   SHOW ALL RESULTS   ---------------------------
# ====================================================================

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))

plt.subplot(2, 2, 1)
plt.imshow(binary, cmap='gray')
plt.title("Binary Image")
plt.axis('off')

plt.subplot(2, 2, 2)
plt.imshow(opening_result, cmap='gray')
plt.title("Opening (Erosion  Dilation)")
plt.axis('off')

plt.subplot(2, 2, 3)
plt.imshow(closing_result, cmap='gray')
plt.title("Closing (Dilation  Erosion)")
plt.axis('off')

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

import numpy as np
import cv2
from matplotlib import pyplot as plt

# ----------------------------
# Generic sliding window helper
# ----------------------------
def apply_filter(image, size, func):
    m = size // 2
    padded = np.pad(image, (m, m), mode='constant', constant_values=0)
    output = np.zeros_like(image)

    for i in range(image.shape[0]):
        for j in range(image.shape[1]):
            region = padded[i:i+size, j:j+size]
            output[i, j] = func(region)
    
    return output


# ----------------------------
# Filters (manual)
# ----------------------------

def median_filter(image, size=3):
    return apply_filter(image, size, lambda r: np.median(r))

def max_filter(image, size=3):
    return apply_filter(image, size, lambda r: np.max(r))

def min_filter(image, size=3):
    return apply_filter(image, size, lambda r: np.min(r))

def midpoint_filter(image, size=3):
    return apply_filter(image, size, lambda r: (np.max(r) + np.min(r)) // 2)


# ----------------------------
# MAIN (Jupyter output)
# ----------------------------

img = cv2.imread(r"C:\Users\Admin\OneDrive\Pictures\Your paragraph text.png", 0)

if img is None:
    print("Image not loaded  check path!")
else:
    med = median_filter(img)
    mx = max_filter(img)
    mn = min_filter(img)
    mid = midpoint_filter(img)

    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))

    plt.subplot(2, 3, 1)
    plt.title("Original")
    plt.imshow(img, cmap='gray')
    plt.axis('off')

    plt.subplot(2, 3, 2)
    plt.title("Median Filter")
    plt.imshow(med, cmap='gray')
    plt.axis('off')

    plt.subplot(2, 3, 3)
    plt.title("Max Filter")
    plt.imshow(mx, cmap='gray')
    plt.axis('off')

    plt.subplot(2, 3, 4)
    plt.title("Min Filter")
    plt.imshow(mn, cmap='gray')
    plt.axis('off')

    plt.subplot(2, 3, 5)
    plt.title("Midpoint Filter")
    plt.imshow(mid, cmap='gray')
    plt.axis('off')

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

import cv2
import numpy as np
from matplotlib import pyplot as plt

img = cv2.imread(r"D:\3rd sem\garden-flower-close-up-35646.jpg", 0)
img = img.astype(np.float32) / 255.0

# --------------------------------------
# 1) Gaussian Noise (strong)
# --------------------------------------
gaussian = img + np.random.normal(0, 0.15, img.shape)
gaussian = np.clip(gaussian, 0, 1)

# --------------------------------------
# 2) Salt & Pepper Noise (strong)
# --------------------------------------
s_p = img.copy()
prob = 0.10
rnd = np.random.rand(*img.shape)

s_p[rnd < prob/2] = 0
s_p[rnd > 1 - prob/2] = 1

# --------------------------------------
# 3) Uniform Noise (strong)
# --------------------------------------
uniform = img + np.random.uniform(-0.2, 0.2, img.shape)
uniform = np.clip(uniform, 0, 1)

# --------------------------------------
# 4) Rayleigh Noise (strong)
# --------------------------------------
rayleigh_noise = np.random.rayleigh(scale=0.3, size=img.shape)
rayleigh = img + rayleigh_noise
rayleigh = np.clip(rayleigh, 0, 1)

# --------------------------------------
# 5) Exponential Noise (strong)
# --------------------------------------
exp_noise = np.random.exponential(scale=0.2, size=img.shape)
exponential = img + exp_noise
exponential = np.clip(exponential, 0, 1)

# --------------------------------------
# 6) Gamma Noise (strong)
# --------------------------------------
gamma_noise = np.random.gamma(shape=4, scale=0.08, size=img.shape)
gamma = img + gamma_noise
gamma = np.clip(gamma, 0, 1)

# --------------------------------------
# Display the result
# --------------------------------------
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 10))

plt.subplot(2, 3, 1)
plt.title("Gaussian Noise")
plt.imshow(gaussian, cmap='gray')
plt.axis('off')

plt.subplot(2, 3, 2)
plt.title("Salt & Pepper Noise")
plt.imshow(s_p, cmap='gray')
plt.axis('off')

plt.subplot(2, 3, 3)
plt.title("Uniform Noise")
plt.imshow(uniform, cmap='gray')
plt.axis('off')

plt.subplot(2, 3, 4)
plt.title("Rayleigh Noise")
plt.imshow(rayleigh, cmap='gray')
plt.axis('off')

plt.subplot(2, 3, 5)
plt.title("Exponential Noise")
plt.imshow(exponential, cmap='gray')
plt.axis('off')

plt.subplot(2, 3, 6)
plt.title("Gamma Noise")
plt.imshow(gamma, cmap='gray')
plt.axis('off')

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

#restoration filters 

import cv2
import numpy as np
from matplotlib import pyplot as plt

# Load image
img = cv2.imread(r"D:\3rd sem\garden-flower-close-up-35646.jpg", 0)

if img is None:
    print("Image not found!")
else:
    img = img.astype(np.float32) / 255.0
    size = 3
    m = size // 2

    # Pad image
    padded = np.pad(img, (m, m), mode="constant")

    # Output images
    arithmetic = np.zeros_like(img)
    geometric = np.zeros_like(img)
    harmonic = np.zeros_like(img)
    contra_harmonic = np.zeros_like(img)

    Q = 1.5   # Q value for contra-harmonic filter

    # --------------------------------------------
    # Apply Filters Using Built-in Numpy Operations
    # --------------------------------------------
 
    for i in range(img.shape[0]):
        for j in range(img.shape[1]):
            region = padded[i:i+size, j:j+size]

            # Arithmetic Mean
            arithmetic[i, j] = np.mean(region)

            # Geometric Mean
            geometric[i, j] = np.exp(np.mean(np.log(region + 1e-10)))

            # Harmonic Mean
            harmonic[i, j] = 9 / np.sum(1.0 / (region + 1e-10))

            # Contra-Harmonic Mean
            contra_harmonic[i, j] = (
                np.sum(region**(Q + 1)) / (np.sum(region**Q) + 1e-10)
            )

    # --------------------------------------------
    # Display results
    # --------------------------------------------
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 10))

    plt.subplot(2, 2, 1)
    plt.title("Arithmetic Mean Filter")
    plt.imshow(arithmetic, cmap='gray')
    plt.axis('off')

    plt.subplot(2, 2, 2)
    plt.title("Geometric Mean Filter")
    plt.imshow(geometric, cmap='gray')
    plt.axis('off')

    plt.subplot(2, 2, 3)
    plt.title("Harmonic Mean Filter")
    plt.imshow(harmonic, cmap='gray')
    plt.axis('off')

    plt.subplot(2, 2, 4)
    plt.title("Contra-Harmonic Filter (Q=1.5)")
    plt.imshow(contra_harmonic, cmap='gray')
    plt.axis('off')

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()
